[[Religion]] and [[business]] have throughout history interacted in ways that relate to and affected one another, as well as influenced [[sociocultural evolution]], [[political geography|political geographies]], and [[labour law]]s.

==Religious tourism==
{{Main|Religious tourism|Sacred travel}}
Some areas, countries or cities have an economy based on religious tourism. Examples include Islamic [[Hajj]] tourism and [[Holy See|Vatican]] tourism. The hotels and markets of important religious places are a source of income to the locals.<ref>[http://www.upiasia.com/Society_Culture/2008/07/02/indias_booming_business_of_religion/2083/ India's booming business of religion - upiasia.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

===Pilgrimage sites===
{{See also|Pilgrimage|Hajj}}
The boards or shines sometimes receive so much in donations that governments to take it under control for proper utilization of resources and management.<ref>[https://www.maavaishnodevi.org/shrine_board.asp Introduction<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The annual revenues of most of the religious places are not regulated.<ref>[http://www.banned-books.com/truth-seeker/1995archive/122_3/35business.html The Business of Religion<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

==Business ethics==
{{main|Religious views on business ethics}}

===Judaism===
{{main|Jewish business ethics}}
[[Judaism]] outlines requirements of accurate weights and measurements in commerce, as well as prohibitions on monetary deception, verbal deception and misrepresentation.<ref name='Scheinman'>{{citation | first = James | last = Scheinman | contribution = Jewish Business Ethics | title = The Evolution & Impact of Jewish Law | publisher = Regents of the University of California U.C. Davis Journal of International Law & Policy | year = 1995 }}</ref>

==Food processing==

===Halal===
Globally, [[halal]] products comprise a US$2 trillion industry.<ref name='Bladd 2010-09-09'>{{cite news | first = Joanne | last = Bladd |author2=Claire Ferris-Lay  | title = Planet Islamic: the $2trn battle for the halal market | date = 2010-09-09 | url = http://www.arabianbusiness.com/planet-islamic---2trn-battle-for-halal-market-348084.html | work = Arabian Business | accessdate = 2011-05-18}}</ref>

===Kashrut===
As of 2003, the [[Kashrut|kosher]] industry had certified more than 100,000 products, which total approximately US$165 billion in sales annually.<ref name='Shimoni'>{{cite web | url = http://kosherfood.about.com/od/kosherbasics/p/kosherstats.htm | title = 10 Most Interesting Kosher Stats of 2006 | accessdate = 2011-05-18 | last = Shimoni | first = Giora }}</ref>

==Business law==

===United Kingdom===
[[United Kingdom labour law]] prohibits employer discrimination based on religion, belief, or any lack thereof.<ref name='Acas'>{{cite web | url = http://www.acas.org.uk/media/pdf/f/l/religion_1.pdf | title = Religion or Belief and the Workplace | accessdate = 2011-05-18 | format = PDF | work = Acas | quote = From 2 December 2003, when the Employment Equality (Religion or Belief) Regulations came into force, it became unlawful to discriminate against workers because of religion or similar belief.}}</ref>

===United States===
In the [[United States]], [[United States labor law|labor law]]s including [[Civil Rights Act of 1964#Title VII|Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964]] prohibit businesses from discriminating against employees based on the basis of religion.<ref name='Foltin 2004'>{{cite journal | title = Reconciling Faith and Livelihood | journal = Human Rights Magazine | year = 2004 | first = Richard T. | last = Foltin | author2 = James D. Standish | issue = Summer 2004 | url = http://www.americanbar.org/publications/human_rights_magazine_home/summer04_summer04_irr_hr_summer04_reconcile.html | accessdate = 2011-05-18 }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name='Steinberger'>{{cite web | url = http://smallbusiness.yahoo.com/r-article-a-112582-m-5-sc-51-religion_and_the_workplace-i | title = Religion and the Workplace | accessdate = 2011-05-18 | last = Steinberger | first = Jeffrey | date = 2007-09-19 | publisher = [[Entrepreneur (magazine)|Entrepreneur]] | quote = Under Title VII, an employer can't refuse to reasonably accommodate an employee's religious observances, unless accommodation would constitute an "undue hardship" for the business. | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110723235609/http://smallbusiness.yahoo.com/r-article-a-112582-m-5-sc-51-religion_and_the_workplace-i | archivedate = 2011-07-23 | df =  }}</ref> Business law is also at times applied to religious organizations, due to their status as incorporated entities.<ref name='Sternal 2009'>{{cite journal | title = Current Legal Issues Facing Religious Organizations | journal = Business Law Today | date = July–August 2009 | first = Patrick | last = Sternal | volume = 18 | issue = 6 | url = http://apps.americanbar.org/buslaw/blt/2009-07-08/sternal.shtml | accessdate = 2011-05-18}}</ref>

